history: 01-27-2016 in publication since 1965, abacus is a refereed scholarly journal published by wiley on behalf of the accounting foundation, the university of sydney. the publication provides a forum for the expression of independent and critical thought on matters of current academic and professional interest in accounting, finance, and business. articles feature current research, critical evaluation of current developments in theory and practice, analysis of the effects of regulatory framework, and exploration of alternatives to, and explanations of, past and current practices. the content is international in scope, with emphasis on international accounting and accounting history. abacus is published quarterly and is an isi-listed journal. (adams, christine)

title: architectural science review
content type: brings out research papers, research notes, and abstracts of phd dissertations and theses in all areas of architectural science.
editorial description: http://www.tandfonline.com/toc/tasr20/current
language: architectural science   formerly (until 1958) gbr united kingdom
history: 01-27-2016 founded at the university of sydney in australia in 1958, this peer-reviewed quarterly, published by taylor & francis, covers a multitude of topics that fall under the heading of "architectural science." it remains one of the few publications to focus on the subject. the six or more articles and the occasional book reviews in an issue may be on acoustics, structural engineering, environmental systems, sustainability, lighting, digital architecture, or other topics related to the intersections between technology, science, and architecture. australia is well-represented, but overall, the research subjects and case studies are international, as are the scholars and researchers who make up the list of authors. available to libraries as an online-only or print-and-online subscription. recommended for architecture or engineering libraries with a strong research focus. (trendler, amy)

title: archives and manuscripts
content type: contains articles about the theory and practice of archives work, or relating to archives and recordkeeping.
editorial description: http://www.archivists.org.au/learning-publications/archives-and-manuscripts
language: bulletin for australian archivists   formerly (until 1955) aus australia
history: 01-27-2016 the triannually published journal archives and manuscripts, which is peer-reviewed and published by the australian society of archivists, inc., aims to inform its national archives community about the "theory and practice of archives and record-keeping." the audience is primarily professionals, educators, researchers, and students. the country's diversity, along with occasional perspective from new zealand and fiji, is a basis for critical insight and analysis in articles about adoption records and archives and their use with child-abuse victims archival education and literacy around indigenous communities and archival ethics related to such issues. the journal includes an "international notes" section, which describes regional archival practices, current projects of interest, and literature reviews. article abstracts are available online. the latest issue was a special issue entitled "participatory archives in a world of ubiquitous media." professionals looking to explore nontraditional archives, or collections that pertain to indigenous groups, would find archives and manuscripts very useful. (williams, stacie)

history: 03-15-2000 art and australia is a regional publication that provides coverage of the contemporary art scene in australia. among the visual arts, particular attention is given to painting and sculpture and some historical pieces are included as well. articles regularly feature australian artists, art galleries in major cities, and exhibition news. the "art directory" in each issue also includes information about important gallery acquisitions, art auction prices, and art competitions. recent books received are also listed. this periodical is particularly useful for keeping current with and studying art from this part of the world. mary n. hernandez

title: australian and new zealand journal of criminology
content type: presents a professional eclectic approach to the tertiary field of criminology by promoting quality research and debate on crime and criminal justice.
editorial description: http://www.uk.sagepub.com/journals/journal202004
history: 01-27-2016 australian and new zealand journal of criminology is the official journal of the australian and new zealand society of criminology (anzsoc). it began as a quarterly publication in 1968, but since 1991, it has been published three times a year. the journal is "dedicated to advancing research and debate on a range of criminological problems and embraces diverse, methodological approaches, being home to a wide range of criminological and interdisciplinary work in the field of crime and criminal justice." as one would expect, most of the articles are authored by australian or new zealand researchers, and address issues pertaining to those countries, but articles by american, canadian, and other international criminologists are sometimes included. each issue contains six to eight peer-reviewed research articles, and frequently opens with an editorial introduction. book reviews are often included. full-text access is available through sage. (marcus, elizabeth)

title: australian geographer
content type: focuses on environmental studies particularly the biophysical environment and its interactions with humans.
editorial description: http://www.tandfonline.com/toc/cage20/.vculimksdgg#.vcv13sksdgg
history: 01-27-2016 published under the auspices of the geographical society of new south wales, australian geographer offers research articles on human and physical geography, focusing on environmental studies. there is a strong australian concentration, but with articles on the broader asia-pacific and antarctic regions. occasional special issues on focused topics are published. editorship/authorship is largely australian. important for academic libraries that support geography departments, and environmental or area studies programs with australasian interests. (burchsted, fred)

title: australian journal of education
editorial description: provides information to educational researchers as well as educators, administrators and policymakers about issues of concern in education. also provides research studies that contribute to educational knowledge and research methodologies.
reviews (mfl): 01-27-2016 this journal publishes papers on the theory and practice of education, especially as related to australia and its neighboring countries. embracing all fields of education and training, it aims to inform educational researchers as well as educators, administrators, and policymakers about issues of contemporary concern in education. articles include original research, research reviews, policy analyses, commentary on previously published articles, and occasional book reviews. the authors represent an international corps of scholars from a broad range of disciplines, such as philosophy, psychology, political science, economics, history, anthropology, medicine, and sociology. recent articles have discussed transitions for students with disabilities in new south wales, program evaluation, the use of tablets in the classroom and beyond, and the handwriting experiences of left-handed primary school students in australia. recommended for academic libraries. url: http://aed.sagepub.com/ (godbey, samantha)
reviews (other): editorial description     provides information to educational researchers as well as educators, administrators and policymakers about issues of concern in education. also provides research studies that contribute to educational knowledge and research methodologies.

history 2: australian journal of mental retardation 0045-0634 (until 1980) aus australia
reviews (mfl): 03-11-2008 this scholarly quarterly is the official journal of the australasian society for the study of intellectual disability.  it is international and multidisciplinary in scope, and publishes original research papers, literature reviews, and conceptual articles.  issues generally contain four or five research articles and one or two brief reports.  recent research articles include "the relationship between food refusal and social skills in persons with intellectual disabilities" and "parents' perspectives on the communication skills of their children with severe disabilities."  also included in some issues are "data briefs" that contain summaries of significant current data (usually national data) on trends in demographics, service provision, expenditure, and other issues.  there is also an opinions and perspectives section that provides a forum for discussion and debate about current issues.  most issues include two or three book reviews.  there are occasional special or theme issues.  recommended for comprehensive academic collections. (naylor, sharon)

title: international journal of music education
editorial description: provides academic papers on various aspects of music education throughout the world.
language 1: summaries in spanish
history: music education international 1448-3238 incorporates (2002-2003) aus australia
reviews (mfl): 01-16-2013 this journal is published quarterly by the international society for music education, and the issues in each volume are split between "research" and "practice." its scholarly articles cover topics such as ethnographic studies in music teaching, research done on various schools of pedagogy, and historical perspectives of teaching around the world.  its international focus is demonstrated through the inclusion of abstracts in french, german, spanish, and english (though each article itself is in english). in addition to abstracts, keywords are listed for each article. the content is relevant to music teachers whose students are at all levels, and is recommended for academic libraries. (cross, abigail)
reviews (other): editorial description     provides academic papers on various aspects of music education throughout the world.

title: australian journal of politics and history
subjectcodes: history - history of australasia and other areas, political science
editorial description: contains articles in the fields of international politics, australian foreign policy, and australia's relations with the countries of the asia-pacific region.
reviews (mfl): 03-22-2007 this widely indexed, refereed scholarly journal has been published quarterly in australia since 1955. it is an excellent resource for "the politics and history of australia and modern europe, intellectual history, political history, the history of political thought, international politics, australian foreign policy, and australia's relations with the countries of the asia-pacific region." the journal includes articles, shorter critical notices and research notes, controversies, and symposia. there are occasionally special issues on a particular theme or topic of contemporary political and historical interest. this journal's review section is very high quality, providing good assessments on contemporary political history. articles are well researched and well written for both experts and educated general readers. recent article topics include "from ambivalence to influence: australia and the negotiation of the 1968 nuclear non-proliferation treaty" and "patterns and directions in australian politics over the past fifty years." some recent reviews include "unfolding history: the chinese in new zealand," "platypus and parliament: the australian senate in theory and practice," and "legacies of white australia: race, culture, nation."  the web site, www.blackwellpublishing.com/journal.asp?ref=0004-9522&site=1, provides the aims and scope of the journal, tables of contents, abstracts of recent issues, and one free sample issue to view online. this is an excellent resource, highly recommended for academic, research, and academic libraries serving patrons studying, teaching, or having interest in the politics and history of the pacific area.

reviews (mfl): 01-27-2016 the australian & new zealand journal of statistics is divided into two main sections. one covers topics in applications (with such recent topics as curved fibrous objects in 3d, seismological data, and breast cancer). the other covers theory and methods (with such recent topics as regression using uncertain prior information, multi-arm clinic trials, and non-crossing quantile regression curves). reviews and historical or general-interest papers are also accepted. issues end with book reviews and a list of forthcoming papers. issues typically run around 100b2150 pages, with articles in the 10- to 20-page range. recommended for libraries that serve colleges or universities with a statistics program. (dotson, danny)

title: australian literary studies
editorial description: features articles on australian literature, and on matters of concern to literary scholars in australia.
reviews (mfl): 02-01-2011 from the university of queensland press, this peer-reviewed journal "publishes scholarship and criticism on australian literature, and on matters of concern to literary scholars in australia." recent articles cover topics on "eco-humanities," adapting australian novels for the theatre, world wars i and ii, and paternalism. recently featured authors include marion halligan, alexis wright, shirley hazzard, and christos tsiolkas. articles tend to be 10b215 pages long. in addition to literary criticism, the journal incorporates author interviews, book reviews, and an "annual bibliography of studies in australian literature." useful for academic libraries that serve programs in australian, postcolonial, and/or world literatures. public libraries that collect australian literature and related studies will also be interested in this journal. (hb) (buchanan, heidi)
reviews (other): editorial description     features articles on australian literature, and on matters of concern to literary scholars in australia.

title: australian veterinary journal
editorial description: provides an essential forum for the dissemination of leading edge veterinary research.
history: australian veterinary association. journal   formerly (until 1927) gbr united kingdom
reviews (mfl): 01-27-2016 the australian veterinary journal is the official journal of the australian veterinary association. scientific and clinical articles are peer-reviewed, and a typical issue includes original research and reviews, case reports and series, clinical updates, and letters on all aspects of veterinary science, particularly their significance to australasian veterinary medicine. the content is easily readable and includes many color photos, but will appeal mostly to the target audience of veterinary professionals, as they would gain the most from the clinical and scientific articles. as the premier veterinary science journal for australian veterinary association members and subscribers, this journal provides a uniquely australian perspective, including indigenous species and issues specific to geographic locations in australia. the journal provides equal parts association news and scientific articles, with the research articles subdivided into sections on production animals, equine, small animals, wildlife and zoos, and avian. this journal also includes book reviews that would be helpful to identifying veterinary-related books for a library collection. diagnostic challenge articles are intended to "highlight the usefulness of investigative techniques in formulating a diagnosis." the online format provides access to issues dating back to volume 1 (1925). the publisher, john wiley & sons, inc., includes an option for authors to pay charges that would make their article freely available so an issue may have one or two articles designated with the open access symbol. this journal is most appropriate for academic institutions with a veterinary or animal science program. url: http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/journal/10.1111/%28issn%291751-0813 (ugaz, ana)

title: bulletin of indonesian economic studies
subjectcodes: business and economics - economic situation and conditions
editorial description: contains a survey of recent developments in the economy, 3 or 4 articles by specialist writers, and notes on special topics.
reviews (mfl): 03-22-2007 this refereed scholarly journal has been issued three times a year since 1965. it publishes high-quality research by both indonesians and foreigners on any and all matters pertaining to the indonesian economy, including poverty, public administration, small business, state enterprise, peasant farming, fisheries, and financial crises. some articles are on closely related fields such as "law, the environment, demography, education and health." this is an excellent resource for understanding the economics of indonesia in the international environment. articles are heavily cited. each issue includes a comprehensive "survey of recent developments," which is designed especially for those without an economics background.  there are also book reviews on indonesian economics and related issues. one recent article discusses how new local governments are being created as indonesia decentralizes. another deals with the low reported numbers of ethnic chinese in indonesia during the 2000 census and how that low number might represent fears of repeated anti-chinese violence. recent reviews include "recollections: the indonesian economy: 1950sb21990s" and "decentralisation in indonesia: redesigning the state." occasionally there are special issues, such as a recent one devoted to "indonesia's crisis in retrospect," a discussion of indonesia's economic and banking crisis. the web site, www.tandf.co.uk/journals/titles/00074918.asp, provides tables of contents and free viewing of a sample issue with free registration. this journal is an excellent source of economic information for this populous and important region. it is well written and designed for a wide range of readers. highly recommended for all types of libraries. (xiong, anna)

title: australian historical studies
editorial description: includes articles and reviews on australian history.
history: historical studies 0018-2559 former titles (until 1988) aus australia
history 1: historical studies, australia and new zealand 0728-6023 (until 1967) aus australia
reviews (mfl): 03-22-2007 this long-established, refereed scholarly journal has been published since 1940 by the university of melbourne in australia. in the past 65 years, it has become one of the most respected journals dealing with australian, new zealand, and pacific regional issues. contributors are academic experts. the journal is an excellent resource for information on the "heritage and conservation of places, archaeology, visual display in museums and galleries, oral history, family history and histories of place, significant historical subjects of general interest to the readers and practitioners of australian history" and more. issues are divided into discrete sections: "articles," "forum," "historical overview," "debate," "obituaries," and "reviews." recent articles include "regulating the labour market in australia's wartime democracy," "re-membering australasia: a repressed memory," and "the power of pictures: learning-by-looking at papua in illustrated newspapers and magazines." book reviews and review essays are included. recent reviews include "the irish in new zealand," "from white australia to woomera: the story of australian immigrants," and "boundary markers."  occaionally there are special issues, such as a recent one on "visualizing australia's past. war and peace."  the web site, www.ahs.unimelb.edu.au, provides covers and tables of contents for past issues, subscription and submission information, and sample book reviews. this well-illustrated journal is a great resource for both scholars and educated general readers interested in australian history. highly recommended for academic libraries, especially those supporting asia/pacific studies programs, and public libraries.
